"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Ephesians chapters 5–6
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-ephesians-5-6.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/ephesians.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/ephesians.json (MKT text)
- data/parallels/ephesians.json (Gen 2:24 at 5:31; Exod 20:12 at 6:2)
- data/commentary/mkt-christ/ephesians.json (chapters 1–4, for continuity)

Key decisions in this range:
- "Paul" throughout (consistent with chs 1–4 script)
- Gen 2:24 (5:31) classified as type — Paul's own disclosure at 5:32 makes this explicit
- 5:32 ("I am talking about Christ and the church") treated as the most direct typological
  statement in Ephesians — marriage as institution was designed as a type
- Armor of God sequence (6:10–17) classified shadow/fulfillment: Isa 59:17 and 11:5
  are the OT ground; Christ embodied the armor; believers receive it through union with him
- 5:14 hymn fragment classified direct: resurrection language applied to believers via
  Christ's own resurrection, echoing Isa 60:1 and 26:19
- Household code (5:22–6:9) framed throughout as an extension of the Christ-church
  analogy — the domestic relationships are not the primary datum; Christ is
- 6:17 "sword of the Spirit = word of God" connected to Christ as the Word (John 1:1;
  Rev 19:15); the weapon is Christ mediated through the Spirit
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html


EPHESIANS = {
  "5": {
    "1": '<p>The theme of divine image-bearing fulfilled in Christ: Paul calls believers to be "imitators of God as dearly loved children." The capacity to imitate God rests on adoption into the family of the Son — the one who is "the image of the invisible God" (Col 1:15) and who said "Anyone who has seen me has seen the Father" (John 14:9). Christ is the ground of the command: believers can imitate God because they have been placed in the Son who perfectly images the Father.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "Christ loved us and gave himself up for us as a fragrant offering and sacrifice to God" applies to Christ the Levitical language of the burnt offering — every complete offering ascended to God as a <em>rēach nīchoach</em> (fragrant aroma, Lev 1:9, 13, 17), a voluntary gift that secured acceptance before God. Ps 40:6-8, quoted in Heb 10:5-7, explicitly identifies the offering of the body of Christ as the event that replaces the entire sacrificial system. Christ does not merely bring a sacrifice; he is the sacrifice.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The theme of covenant holiness grounded in Christ\'s sanctifying work: the prohibition of sexual immorality and greed among God\'s holy people echoes Lev 19:2 ("be holy as I the Lord your God am holy") and the broader purity demands of the Mosaic covenant. In Ephesians the basis has shifted: it is Christ who sanctifies the church, cleansing her to be holy and blameless (5:26-27). The ethics of holiness are not self-generated but are the outworking of what Christ has already done.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A revelation of God: the replacement of obscenity and foolish talk with thanksgiving names the appropriate speech of a people who know what God has done in Christ. Paul\'s dominant vocabulary throughout the letter is eucharistic — the gospel creates gratitude (1:3-14; 5:20). The ethics of speech are shaped not by moral effort but by the reality the gospel announces: a sacrifice has been offered and accepted; thanksgiving is the only fitting response.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A direct Christological claim of eschatological weight: "no immoral, impure or greedy person — such a person is an idolater — has any inheritance in the kingdom of Christ and of God." The unusual phrase "kingdom of Christ and of God" coordinates Christ and God as joint sovereigns over the coming inheritance — an implicit claim about Christ\'s participation in divine rule (1 Cor 15:24-28; Rev 11:15). The inheritance that was Israel\'s land-promise is now the eschatological kingdom that only Christ can grant.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The theme of Christ\'s cross as the one event that absorbs God\'s wrath: "God\'s wrath comes on those who are disobedient" names the default trajectory from which the cross rescues. Paul\'s parallel in Rom 5:9 is explicit — "we shall be saved from God\'s wrath through him." The present tense ("comes") signals an already-active wrath; the gospel is not a precaution against a future threat but an escape from an existing one, accomplished at the cross.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The theme of the two-kingdom separation effected by Christ: "do not be partners with them" applies to believers the separation Christ accomplished between the domain of light and the domain of darkness (5:8; Col 1:13 — "rescued us from the dominion of darkness and brought us into the kingdom of the Son"). The call to non-participation is not moral fastidiousness but the practical consequence of having been transferred from one realm to another.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A direct Christological claim: "you were once darkness, but now you are light in the Lord." Christ is "the light of the world" (John 8:12), and the transformation Paul describes — from darkness to light — is the specific fulfillment of Isa 9:2 that Matt 4:15-16 applies to Jesus\'s Galilean ministry. The phrase "in the Lord" is decisive: the change of state is not moral improvement but a change of location — being transferred into the One who is light.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The theme of the Spirit reproducing Christ\'s character: "the fruit of the light consists in all goodness, righteousness and truth" describes qualities that are simultaneously ethical requirements and descriptions of Christ\'s own character — the one who is "holy, righteous and true" (Rev 3:7; 16:5). The Galatians parallel (fruit of the Spirit, Gal 5:22-23) confirms that these are not self-cultivated virtues but the harvest of Christ\'s Spirit at work in the new-covenant community.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A revelation of God: "find out what pleases the Lord" names Christ as the Lord whose will now governs all of life — replacing the Mosaic law as the moral reference point (see 2:15; 4:20-21). The new-covenant promise of Jer 31:34 — "they shall all know me" — is fulfilled through the Spirit who teaches what Christ requires (John 14:26; 16:13). Moral discernment is not primarily rational but relational: knowing Christ determines what pleases him.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The theme of Christ as the light that exposes what darkness conceals: "expose the fruitless deeds of darkness" extends the light-metaphor Christologically. John 3:20-21 identifies Jesus as the Light before whom every hidden deed is disclosed; John 1:5 — "the light shines in the darkness, and the darkness has not overcome it." The believer\'s call to expose darkness is a participation in Christ\'s own ministry of illumination.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A revelation of God: the shame attached to what the disobedient do in secret measures their distance from the holiness of God made visible in Christ. The verse does not require comment but functions as a negative pointer: sin hides from light because light is Christ\'s domain, and shame marks every action that cannot bear his presence. The same logic underlies 1 John 1:5-7 — walking in the light means living as if Christ\'s character is the standard by which all actions are assessed.</p>',
    "13": '<p>The theme of Christ as the light in whom all things are made manifest: "everything exposed by the light becomes visible — and everything that is illuminated becomes a light." John 1:4-5 identifies the light with the life of Christ; John 3:21 describes coming to the light as the movement of those who do truth. The principle at work is Christological: the light of Christ\'s character and resurrection is the only force that can reveal the true nature of what lies in darkness.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A direct Christological application: the early Christian hymn fragment — "Wake up, sleeper, rise from the dead, and Christ will shine on you" — applies resurrection language to believers by grounding it in Christ\'s own resurrection. Isa 60:1 ("Arise, shine, for your light has come") and Isa 26:19 ("your dead will live; their bodies will rise") provide the OT register; Isa 9:2 identifies this arising with the dawning of light on those in the shadow of death. The hymn declares that Christ\'s resurrection is the force that awakens the spiritually dead — his shining is the cause, not the result, of the awakening.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The theme of wisdom fulfilled in Christ: the contrast between unwise and wise recalls Prov 1:7 and the Wisdom literature\'s entire project — the search for the way of life that conforms to God\'s ordering of creation. Paul identifies Christ explicitly as "the wisdom of God" (1 Cor 1:24, 30) and "in whom are hidden all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge" (Col 2:3). Walking wisely is not about prudential calculation but about ordering life according to the One in whom wisdom is embodied.</p>',
    "16": '<p>The theme of Christ as the redeemer of time: "redeeming the time, because the days are evil" (<em>exagorazomenoi ton kairon</em>) uses the same redemption vocabulary as Gal 4:4-5 — "God sent his Son... to redeem those under the law." The "evil days" of the present age are the domain of "the ruler of the kingdom of the air" (2:2); Christ has broken that dominion, and believers participate in the eschatological purchase of time from the power that squanders it.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A revelation of God: "understand what the Lord\'s will is" — where the "Lord" is Christ — names Christ as the source of the moral intelligence that replaces foolishness. The promise of Col 1:9 ("filled with the knowledge of his will through all spiritual wisdom") and the identification of Christ as "the way and the truth" (John 14:6) establish that understanding the Lord\'s will is inseparable from knowing the Lord himself. Discernment is Christocentric.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A direct Christological claim: Spirit-filling is the fruit of Christ\'s ascension. John 7:39 — "the Spirit had not yet been given, since Jesus had not yet been glorified" — makes the connection explicit. Acts 2:33 — "exalted to the right hand of God... he has received from the Father the promised Holy Spirit and has poured out what you now see and hear." To be filled with the Spirit is to receive the gift that only the ascended Christ can give; the command presupposes what Christ has accomplished.</p>',
    "19": '<p>The theme of the Psalter fulfilled in Christ: the community is to speak "psalms, hymns, and songs from the Spirit... to the Lord." The OT Psalter supplied the liturgical vocabulary of Israel — and many psalms are read in the NT as pointing forward to Christ (Ps 22 at the crucifixion; Ps 110 at the exaltation; Ps 2 at the resurrection). Singing "to the Lord" — where the Lord is the risen Christ — means the entire hymnody of Israel is now reoriented toward its fulfillment and focus.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A direct Christological claim: "always giving thanks to God the Father for everything, in the name of our Lord Jesus Christ." The phrase "in the name" places Christ as the mediator through whom all worship reaches the Father — the practical outworking of 2:18 ("through him we both have access to the Father by one Spirit") and 3:12. John 14:13-14 grounds this: "whatever you ask in my name, I will do it." Thanksgiving itself is an act of Christological mediation.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A revelation of God: mutual submission flows from "reverence for Christ" (<em>en phobō Christou</em>). The Christ who "did not consider equality with God something to be used to his own advantage" and "made himself nothing" (Phil 2:6-7) is the model for every act of voluntary deference. The entire household code that follows (5:22–6:9) is grounded in this single verse: every relationship is governed not by social convention but by the pattern Christ established in his own self-emptying.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A shadow of the Christ-church relationship applied domestically: "submit to your own husbands as to the Lord" does not make husbands lords; it maps the wife\'s submission onto the church\'s submission to Christ (v24). The shadow runs from the Christ-church reality to the marriage pattern — Christ-church is primary; husband-wife derives its structure from it. The wife submits not because of her husband\'s authority in isolation but because the marriage relationship is a type of the church\'s relationship to Christ.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A direct Christological claim: "Christ is the head of the church, his body, of which he is the Savior." This is the foundational datum Paul has stated in 1:22 and 4:15; here it governs domestic ethics. The threefold description — head, body, Savior — reflects the cosmic Christology of chapters 1–4 applied to the marriage analogy. The husband-head pattern is a derived application of the Christ-head reality, not its theological equal; the Christological statement is primary.</p>',
    "24": '<p>A revelation of God: the church\'s submission to Christ is the theological norm from which household ethics is derived. The phrase "in everything" applied to the church\'s submission to Christ is absolute — there is no domain of life outside Christ\'s lordship. Paul applies this norm to marriage with "so also" — the domestic relationship participates in the structure of the Christ-church relationship, not the reverse. The order of statement is theologically deliberate.</p>',
    "25": '<p>A direct Christological claim and the most explicit christologizing of domestic ethics in the NT: "husbands, love your wives, just as Christ loved the church and gave himself up for her." The cross is the norm for spousal love — not affection, not eros, but the self-expenditure of Gethsemane and Golgotha. The Levitical code knew many duties; Paul here identifies a love that has no OT domestic precedent, derived entirely from the character of Christ\'s act at the cross.</p>',
    "26": '<p>A direct Christological claim: Christ "sanctify and cleansed" the church "by the washing with water through the word." The priestly-kingly role of Christ echoes Ezek 16:9 (God washing Jerusalem clean) and the Levitical purification rites; Heb 9:14 — "how much more will the blood of Christ... cleanse our consciences." The "word" through which the washing occurs is the gospel word about Christ himself — the proclamation that both announces and effects the cleansing it describes.</p>',
    "27": '<p>A type pointing to eschatological fulfillment: the presentation of the church as "a radiant bride, without stain or wrinkle or any other blemish, holy and blameless" draws on the bridegroom-bride imagery of Isa 62:5 (God rejoicing over Jerusalem as a bridegroom) and the Song of Solomon\'s beloved. The eschatological trajectory runs from these OT figures through to Rev 19:7-8 ("the wedding of the Lamb has come, and his bride has made herself ready") and Rev 21:2 (the new Jerusalem "prepared as a bride"). Christ is the divine bridegroom preparing his people for the eternal marriage.</p>',
    "28": '<p>A revelation of God: the call for husbands to love their wives "as their own bodies" is grounded in the union between Christ and the church stated in v30 — "we are members of his body." Because Christ loves the church as his own body (nourishing and cherishing it, v29), the husband\'s love for his wife as his own body is a participation in the love-structure that governs the primary relationship. The domestic ethic is derivative of the Christological reality.</p>',
    "29": '<p>A direct Christological claim: "just as Christ does the church" — Christ nourishes (<em>ektrefei</em>) and cherishes (<em>thalpei</em>) the church as though caring for his own body. These are not abstract descriptions of divine benevolence but a claim about the ongoing relation of the risen Christ to his people. The body of Christ (1:23; 4:4, 16) is the living organism Christ perpetually sustains; believers are the beneficiaries of a care that is structurally identical to his care for himself.</p>',
    "30": '<p>A direct Christological claim: "we are members of his body" — the body-of-Christ ecclesiology is the foundation on which the marriage analogy rests (vv23-29) and the reason the husband\'s love for his wife is structurally connected to Christ\'s love for the church. This membership is not organizational but ontological — union with Christ (John 15:4-5; 1 Cor 6:15; 12:12-27). The verse is brief because it restates a theme central to the entire letter.</p>',
    "31": '<p>A type fulfilled: Paul quotes Gen 2:24 — "a man will leave his father and mother and be united to his wife, and the two will become one flesh" — as evidence for the union of Christ and the church, which he discloses explicitly in the next verse. The primordial marriage was designed by God as a type of the Christ-church union: the "leaving" of the father anticipates the Son\'s coming from the Father; the "cleaving" to the wife anticipates the incarnation and cross; the "one flesh" anticipates the church as Christ\'s own body. The type was embedded in creation at the beginning.</p>',
    "32": '<p>A direct typological disclosure: "This is a profound mystery — but I am talking about Christ and the church." This is the most explicit typological statement in Ephesians and one of the most explicit in the NT: Paul announces that the mystery hidden in Gen 2:24 is the union of Christ and the church. Marriage as an institution was designed from creation to be a sign pointing toward its own anti-type. The "profound mystery" (<em>mystērion mega</em>) is not that marriage is meaningful, but that it was always about Christ.</p>',
    "33": '<p>A revelation of God: the domestic application ("let each love his wife... and the wife must respect her husband") brings the cosmic Christology of vv22-32 into the household. The mutual ethic — sacrificial love from the husband, honor from the wife — mirrors in miniature what Christ and the church are to each other: the head who gives himself and the body that responds with reverence. The Christ-church relationship is not an illustration of marriage; marriage is an icon of Christ and the church.</p>'
  },
  "6": {
    "1": '<p>The theme of filial obedience fulfilled in Christ: "children, obey your parents in the Lord, for this is right" is grounded in Christ as the one who perfectly embodied this obedience. Heb 5:8 — "although he was the Son, he learned obedience from what he suffered" — identifies Jesus as the child who obeyed the Father absolutely; Luke 2:51 shows this in its domestic form. The phrase "in the Lord" means the child\'s obedience participates in the pattern Christ himself established, not merely a social convention.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A type transformed in Christ: the fifth commandment (Exod 20:12; Deut 5:16) embedded a land-promise in the obligation to honor parents — "that your days may be long in the land the Lord your God is giving you." Matt 5:5 — "the meek will inherit the earth" — reveals that Christ transforms the land-promise into the eschatological inheritance of the renewed creation. The commandment is not abolished but fulfilled: the promise of "long life" now points toward the resurrection life Christ inaugurated.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A revelation of God: "that it may go well with you and that you may enjoy long life on the earth" — the land-promise attached to the fifth commandment finds its ultimate reference in the earth that Christ will renew (Rev 21:1; Rom 8:21). The covenant structure that linked obedience to dwelling in the land (Deut 28) is not discarded but reconfigured around Christ\'s resurrection as the first-fruits of the renewed creation. Obedience to parents is practiced in the context of a world that Christ is reclaiming.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A revelation of God: "bring them up in the training and instruction of the Lord" — the "Lord" whose instruction shapes the child is Christ. Col 1:28 — "admonishing and teaching everyone with all wisdom, so that we may present everyone fully mature in Christ" — and Col 3:16 — "let the word of Christ dwell among you richly as you teach and admonish one another" — make explicit that the content of this formation is Christ himself. Parental instruction in the Lord is participation in the Spirit\'s work of forming Christ in the next generation.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A revelation of God: the christologizing of labor — "obey your earthly masters... just as you would obey Christ" — does not baptize the institution of slavery but transforms the motivation and horizon of every form of work. Christ is the ultimate master before whom all human authority structures are transparent; the obedience rendered "in sincerity of heart" is ultimately rendered to him. The principle extends beyond slavery: all legitimate labor is service to Christ (Col 3:23-24).</p>',
    "6": '<p>A direct Christological claim: "as slaves of Christ, doing the will of God from the heart." The primary identity is "slave of Christ" (<em>douloi Christou</em>) — the title Paul uses for himself (Rom 1:1; Phil 1:1) and the OT uses for the prophets (Amos 3:7; Jer 7:25). Christ is the master whose will supersedes and relativizes all other masters. Human employers hold a delegated authority; Christ holds the original. Work done from the heart is worship rendered to the lord who bought the worker.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A revelation of God: "serve wholeheartedly, as if you were serving the Lord, not people" — the Lord is Christ, and this identification elevates every act of work into an act of worship. The principle echoes the Levitical logic that service rendered to God\'s people is service rendered to God (Num 8:11); in Christ it is extended: service to any person "in the Lord" is service to Christ himself. Matt 25:40 — "whatever you did for one of the least of these brothers and sisters of mine, you did for me" — is the Christological ground.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A direct Christological claim: "the Lord will reward each one for whatever good they do, whether slave or free." Christ is identified as the eschatological rewarder — the one who renders just recompense regardless of social status. Matt 25:34-40 grounds this: the rewards at the final judgment are given by Christ himself for service rendered (unknowingly) to him. Col 3:24 is the direct parallel: "you will receive an inheritance from the Lord as a reward; it is the Lord Christ you are serving."</p>',
    "9": '<p>A direct Christological claim: Christ is "both their Master and yours" — the one impartial lord before whom all human hierarchy is relativized. The OT ground is Deut 10:17 — "the Lord your God... shows no partiality and accepts no bribes" — now applied to Christ as the cosmic judge. The master who threatens his slaves faces the same judge as the slave who disobeys unjustly. Christ\'s impartiality dismantles the social weaponization of power by placing every human being under the same eschatological accountability.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A direct Christological claim: "be strong in the Lord and in his mighty power" — the "mighty power" (<em>kratei tēs ischuos autou</em>) is the resurrection power described in 1:19-20. "In the Lord" is the sphere of Christ, the domain into which believers are placed by union with him. The command does not invite believers to summon their own reserves; it directs them to draw from the inexhaustible power of the One who defeated death and was raised to fill all things (4:10).</p>',
    "11": '<p>A shadow fulfilled in Christ: the "full armor of God" echoes Isa 59:17 — YHWH himself clothed in righteousness as a breastplate and salvation as a helmet as he came to act where no human agent could. Christ embodied this divine armor in his ministry: the devil\'s schemes at the temptation (Matt 4:1-11) were repelled through the word of God; the cross itself was the act in which God\'s own righteousness confronted the "accuser of our brothers" (Rev 12:10). Believers wear the armor that Christ first wore — it is given, not generated.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A direct Christological claim: "our struggle is not against flesh and blood, but against the rulers, against the authorities, against the powers of this dark world." These are the very powers Christ has already defeated — Col 2:15: "having disarmed the powers and authorities, he made a public spectacle of them, triumphing over them by the cross." The armor is not for a battle still in doubt; it is for holding ground in a victory already secured at the cross. The "rulers" of this dark world have been judged (John 12:31) and disarmed.</p>',
    "13": '<p>The theme of eschatological readiness grounded in Christ\'s accomplished victory: "so that when the day of evil comes, you may be able to stand your ground." The "evil day" echoes prophetic descriptions of divine judgment and final assault (Amos 5:18-20; Dan 12:1); the call to "stand" after having done everything recalls 2:6 — believers are already seated with Christ in the heavenly realms. The armor enables them to maintain the position they already occupy in Christ against the enemies Christ has already defeated.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A shadow fulfilled in Christ: "stand firm with the belt of truth buckled around your waist, with the breastplate of righteousness in place." Isa 11:5 — "righteousness will be his belt and faithfulness the sash around his waist" — applied to the Branch of Jesse, the messianic king; Isa 59:17 — God clothed with righteousness as breastplate. Christ wore these as the righteous king; believers receive both truth and righteousness through union with him — 1 Cor 1:30: "Christ Jesus... has become for us wisdom from God — that is, our righteousness."</p>',
    "15": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "feet fitted with the readiness that comes from the gospel of peace" — Isa 52:7: "how beautiful on the mountains are the feet of those who bring good news, who proclaim peace." Rom 10:15 applies this to NT proclamation, and Eph 2:14 — "he himself is our peace" — identifies Christ as the content of the gospel of peace. The armor item on the feet is the gospel, and the gospel is Christ. The messenger\'s mission is to carry the One who is peace to those who are at war with God.</p>',
    "16": '<p>The theme of faith in Christ as the shield against the accuser: "take up the shield of faith, with which you can extinguish all the flaming arrows of the evil one." The "flaming arrows" evoke accusations, temptations, and doubts — the devil\'s primary weapons in his role as accuser (Rev 12:10; Job 1:9-11). Ps 91:4 — "his faithfulness will be your shield and rampart" — anticipates this; 1 John 5:4 — "the victory that overcomes the world is our faith" — confirms it. Faith in Christ extinguishes what the cross has already answered.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A direct Christological claim on two pieces: "the helmet of salvation" fulfills Isa 59:17 — God\'s own helmet — and "the sword of the Spirit, which is the word of God" identifies the weapon with Christ himself. John 1:1 — Christ is the Word; Heb 4:12-13 — the word of God is living and active, cutting between soul and spirit, judging the thoughts and attitudes of the heart; Rev 19:15 — from Christ\'s mouth comes a sharp sword with which he strikes down the nations. The believer\'s offensive weapon is Christ, wielded through the Spirit.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A direct Christological claim: praying "in the Spirit" is the practical application of the access Christ opened. Eph 2:18 — "through him we both have access to the Father by one Spirit" — is the theological ground; John 14:26; 16:13 — the Spirit teaches and guides because Christ sent him. Rom 8:26-27 — the Spirit intercedes for us in accordance with God\'s will. The prayer life of the church is not self-generated devotion; it flows from Christ\'s mediating work, carried to the Father by the Spirit Christ poured out.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A direct Christological claim: the "mystery of the gospel" Paul asks prayer to make known is Christ among the Gentiles — Col 1:26-27: "the mystery hidden for ages and generations but now disclosed... which is Christ in you, the hope of glory." Eph 3:4-6 defined this mystery: the Gentiles are heirs together with Israel, members together of one body. Paul\'s own speaking is an extension of Christ\'s proclamation — Eph 2:17: "he came and preached peace to you who were far away and peace to those who were near." The ambassador carries the message of the one who sent him.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A shadow of the Servant-pattern: Paul describes himself as "an ambassador in chains" — the suffering envoy imprisoned for the message he carries. The Servant of Isa 42:3 and 49:1-6 was sent with a mission that brought suffering; 2 Cor 5:20 — "we are therefore Christ\'s ambassadors" — makes the pattern explicit. Paul\'s imprisonment for the gospel participates in the Christ-pattern: the one sent suffers so that those to whom he is sent may receive. The chains do not contradict the mission; they extend the cross-pattern.</p>',
    "21": '<p>The theme of the body of Christ maintained through faithful messengers: Tychicus — "the dear brother and faithful servant in the Lord" — functions as a limb of the body carrying news from one part of the body to another. The community of mutual care that Christ builds (4:15-16 — "the whole body, joined and held together by every supporting ligament, grows and builds itself up in love, as each part does its work") is served by such messengers. The practical network of the church\'s life is an expression of Christ\'s body-life.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A revelation of God: the purpose of sending Tychicus — "that you may know how we are and that he may encourage your hearts" — reflects the pastoral character of Christ who said "Peace I leave with you" and promised the Paraclete who "will comfort you" (John 14:16-18, 27). Encouragement in the body of Christ flows from Christ\'s own character as the Comforter, mediated through the Spirit and through the embodied presence of faithful members sent to one another.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A direct Christological claim: the closing blessing — "peace to the brothers and sisters, and love with faith from God the Father and the Lord Jesus Christ" — mirrors the opening salutation of 1:2 ("grace and peace from God our Father and the Lord Jesus Christ"). The letter forms a Christological frame: it opens and closes with grace and peace sourced in the coordinated will of the Father and the Son. The letter\'s final movement, like its first, names Christ alongside the Father as the joint origin of every covenant gift.</p>',
    "24": '<p>A revelation of God: "grace to all who love our Lord Jesus Christ with an undying love" — love for Christ as the defining mark of the covenant people, replacing the OT\'s mark of circumcision. The word translated "undying" (<em>aphtharsia</em>) means incorruptibility or imperishability — the quality of resurrection life (1 Cor 15:42, 50, 53-54: the resurrection body is raised in incorruptibility). The love of God\'s people for Christ is already oriented toward and shaped by the resurrection state; it is a love that the present age cannot extinguish and the next age will perfect.</p>'
  }
}


def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'ephesians')
    merge_comm(existing, EPHESIANS)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'ephesians', existing)
    print('Ephesians 5–6 mkt-christ written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
